<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="7" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[192,1440,1514,1767]" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">
With about 250 described species, 
<taxonomicName box="[653,829,1514,1538]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Sparganothini">Sparganothini</taxonomicName>
are nearly restricted to the New World, with only a handful of species that occur in the Palearctic (
<bibRefCitation author="Powell, J. A. &amp; J. W. Brown" box="[783,1077,1547,1571]" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" refId="ref8787" refString="Powell, J. A., and J. W. Brown. 2012. Tortricoidea, Tortricidae (part): Tortricinae (part): Sparganothini and Atteriini. In: R. W. Hodges (ed.). The Moths of North America, fascicle 8.1. Wedge Entomological Research Foundation; Washington, DC. 230 p." type="book" year="2012">Powell and Brown 2012</bibRefCitation>
). The group has been the subject of considerable recent systematic work with nearly half of the known fauna described since 2005. With exceedingly few exceptions, species of 
<taxonomicName box="[721,897,1612,1636]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Sparganothini">Sparganothini</taxonomicName>
are polyphagous, and although considerable biological information is available for several Nearctic species, owing their pest status, host plant data for Neotropical species were scarce until the work of 
<bibRefCitation author="Janzen, D. H. &amp; W. Hallwachs" box="[827,1189,1677,1701]" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" refId="ref8505" refString="Janzen, D. H., and W. Hallwachs. 2009. Dynamic database for an inventory of the macrocaterpillar fauna, and its food plants and parasitoids, of Area de Conservacion Guanacaste (ACG), northwestern Costa Rica (nn-SRNP-nnnnn voucher codes). Available at http: // janzen. sas. upenn. edu. (Last accessed Dec 12 2018.)" type="url" year="2009">Janzen and Hallwachs (2009)</bibRefCitation>
. In 
<collectingCountry box="[1232,1365,1677,1701]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
, hosts are known for about 40 species, with the data confirming previous concepts of polyphagy for all but 
<taxonomicName authority="Brown, 2013" authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="2013" box="[192,549,1743,1767]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Sparganocosma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[192,386,1743,1766]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">Sparganocosma</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Brown, J. W. &amp; D. H. Janzen &amp; W. Hallwachs" box="[394,549,1743,1767]" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" pagination="53 - 63" refId="ref7725" refString="Brown, J. W., D. H. Janzen, and W. Hallwachs. 2013. A food plant specialist in Sparganothini: A new genus and species from Costa Rica (Lepidoptera: Tortricidae). ZooKeys 303: 53 - 63." type="journal article" year="2013">Brown, 2013</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Brown, J. W. &amp; D. H. Janzen &amp; W. Hallwachs" box="[564,782,1743,1767]" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" pagination="53 - 63" refId="ref7725" refString="Brown, J. W., D. H. Janzen, and W. Hallwachs. 2013. A food plant specialist in Sparganothini: A new genus and species from Costa Rica (Lepidoptera: Tortricidae). ZooKeys 303: 53 - 63." type="journal article" year="2013">Brown et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName authority="Powell and Lambert, 1986" authorityName="Powell and Lambert" authorityYear="1986" box="[850,1331,1742,1767]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Paramorbia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[850,997,1742,1766]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">Paramorbia</emphasis>
Powell and Lambert, 1986
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
